<!---->
      
<!---->
        <div class="base-aside-card__info self-center pl-1 flex flex-col flex-1">
          <h3 class="base-aside-card__title font-sans text-md font-bold text-color-text relative">
            
<!---->          </h3>

<!---->
            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          Stop building links with exact match anchor text.

I've been saying this since 2012.

Most businesses still haven't gotten the memo.

Here's what I see constantly: companies hire an SEO agency, a "link builder" in-house or DIY with a marketplace. 

Every link they get (vast majority of them) uses the exact keyword they want to rank for as the anchor text.

This worked in 2008 when I started. It hasn't worked since Google launched the Penguin update in 2012. 

Since then, there have been four more versions of that update. In 2016, it got baked into the core algorithm.

When every link pointing to your site says "best CRM software," you're not telling Google you're relevant. You're telling Google you're manipulating them.

The result? Over-optimization penalties. Devalued links. Sometimes a full spam penalty.

Think about it this way. If a journalist writes about Coca-Cola and links to their site, what does the anchor text say?

"Coca-Cola." Or "CocaCola.com."

Nobody looks up money keywords and carefully links them. It doesn't happen naturally. Google knows that.

Here's the fix:

Use branded anchor text. Your company name. Your URL. Natural phrases.

In AI search, one of the highest correlated ranking factors is brand mentions. 

So branded anchors now win on two fronts: traditional rankings and AI visibility.

If you're already ranking #7, another exact match link saying "this is what the page is about" adds nothing. Google already knows.

Stop screaming "I'm trying to manipulate you" and start building links that look like what they are: real mentions from real publications.

What's the worst anchor text profile you've ever inherited?
        
            </p>

