            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          I'm working on a non-traditional use for scores this week and that, combined with Casey Hawkins' incredible content around scores lately, I figured I could offer up some additional advice and resources!

These 6 tips will get you cruising with real, reliable data in your HubSpot scores.

🔮 Build your score in a spreadsheet
I'll link my template in the comments for reference. Even with the upgraded lead scoring app, a spreadsheet helps you model out possible lead scores, see all the criteria in one place, and give you a document for internal feedback before you build the scores.

🔮 Separate out your fit score criteria to measure department and seniority as different scoring groups.
You need to know if you're talking to the marketing intern or the marketing executive - one of them has signing power and the other likely doesn't...

🔮 Check your bias and use real data
Demand gen marketers (guilty as charged) want to score their super cool shiny new thing pretty high. But maybe, that new whitepaper just ain't it. Build a test score, run it for a few weeks, then check in with your sales team who is on the receiving end of those leads - there should be data to see how those leads have progressed and the qualitative feedback can give you a reality check of how it's landing with your leads.

🔮 Test your scoring changes in a draft or new score
Don't be like me and accidentally MQL tens of thousands of leads because you pushed the changes live without understanding the downstream impact. Your existing score is likely connected to a LOT of reports and workflows - if you push changes live as soon as you think of them, you might create a big mess for yourself.

🔮 Copy your scores into static properties
Whenever you want to measure a score at a specific moment in time you have to copy it over to capture that snapshot. Like, if you want to know what the activity score was at the moment a contact moved to an Opportunity lifecycle stage, you'll need to create a method to capture that. Maybe someday my wish for dynamic date filtering will come true, but until then, I've got my hacks.

🔮 There are no rules
Well, kinda. I loooove to find ways to use scores to accomplish things OTHER than a sales-readiness threshold. This week's project is looking at scores to help gauge marketing influence in creating and closing deals - it's a fun one (hint: 1 score per marketing channel!)

I revisited our Lunchable GTM Ops episode from Decemeber with Sarah Lane-Hawn🧚‍♀️ that talked about auditing and updating your lead score to help make this lovely list of tips for you - link in comments!
        
            </p>

