            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          Insane stat:

HubSpot’s State of Marketing AI 2025 report found that the average marketing team now runs 11 different AI tools across writing, analytics, and creative work. 

But instead of speeding things up, that variety is starting to slow people down.

Too many options create hesitation and second-guessing. Every new tool comes with a setup, a learning curve, and its own quirks. 

None of those are big individually, but together, they chip away at focus.

Shopify saw the same thing when it built Sidekick AI, its internal automation assistant. 

Marketing teams there went from nine tools to three shared systems. A few months later, creative projects were moving about 25% faster. 

Not because the software changed, but everyone finally used the same one.

You see similar stories across the industry.

Canva’s enterprise rollout this year focused on unifying dozens of disconnected design tools under one shared workspace. 

Adoption jumped almost a third once teams stopped switching between apps.

Adobe’s marketing group is consolidating creative platforms to train one in-house model instead of five external ones.

Creative teams are reaching the same conclusion:

When they stick with one generator long enough to teach it their brand style, the results start to feel human again.

When they jump between tools, that rhythm never builds.

And people do their best work when they’re not constantly changing how they do it.

---

Want growth hacks like this that can catapult your business forward?

Sign up to my weekly growth hacks newsletter for easy-to-implement hacks every Sunday:

&lt;https://lnkd.in/eGMgpwUA&gt;
        
            </p>

